AtomicInteger Class and Volatile Keyword

volatile – Visibility
Problem: Different CPU cores may cache variables, so one thread's update may not be immediately visible to others.

Solution: volatile forces reads/writes to go through main memory, ensuring all threads see the latest value.

Use when:
Simple flags (isRunning, shutdown)
Direct assignment (flag = true)
No read-modify-write operation
 Does NOT provide atomicity.

Example:
volatile boolean running = true;


AtomicInteger – Atomicity

Problem:count++ is Read → Modify → Write, so multiple threads can overwrite each other's updates (race condition).
Solution: AtomicInteger uses CAS (Compare-And-Swap) to make operations atomic without using locks.

Common Methods:
incrementAndGet()
decrementAndGet()
getAndIncrement()
compareAndSet(expected, newValue)

Example:

AtomicInteger count = new AtomicInteger(0);
count.incrementAndGet()  instead of count++ with sync because sync have many problems like deadlock, starvation, etc. so we use atomic classes to avoid these problems.;
